00:47:48.050 --> 00:47:50.900
with new theories to go
beyond the current theory.

00:47:50.900 --> 00:47:55.190
It influences what
experiments we conduct,

00:47:55.190 --> 00:47:58.670
and it influences how
we interpret the results

00:47:58.670 --> 00:47:59.750
of those experiments.

00:47:59.750 --> 00:48:02.924
Feynman gives an example of--

00:48:02.924 --> 00:48:05.090
and this is in, by the way,
his book, "The Character

00:48:05.090 --> 00:48:07.850
of Physical Law", which is a
compilation of the lectures

00:48:07.850 --> 00:48:11.270
that I was going to
play a clip from.

00:48:11.270 --> 00:48:14.300
Feynman gives the
example of someone

00:48:14.300 --> 00:48:17.450
going to a Mayan
astronomer, back

00:48:17.450 --> 00:48:21.120
when the Mayan civilization was
at its peak, and saying, look,

00:48:21.120 --> 00:48:25.700
I know we have this
theory that allows

00:48:25.700 --> 00:48:27.420
us to predict when
eclipses will happen

00:48:27.420 --> 00:48:30.270
and when Venus will transit the
sun and all these other things

00:48:30.270 --> 00:48:31.370
to phenomenal precision.

00:48:31.370 --> 00:48:33.740
But the theory doesn't
tell us what Venus is

00:48:33.740 --> 00:48:34.730
or what the moon is.

00:48:34.730 --> 00:48:38.450
I have a theory that
tells us all those things.

00:48:38.450 --> 00:48:41.210
And then the Mayan astronomer
says, OK but can you

00:48:41.210 --> 00:48:43.094
do the same things we can do.

00:48:43.094 --> 00:48:44.510
And the other guy
says, well no, I

00:48:44.510 --> 00:48:46.375
haven't developed it fully yet.

00:48:46.375 --> 00:48:47.750
It doesn't mean
that we shouldn't

00:48:47.750 --> 00:48:48.800
listen to the other guy.

00:48:48.800 --> 00:48:49.300
Right?

00:48:49.300 --> 00:48:51.110
And it doesn't mean
that even if he

00:48:51.110 --> 00:48:54.080
could get it to work just as
well as Mayan astronomy, that

00:48:54.080 --> 00:48:57.110
doesn't mean that there is no
difference between the choices

00:48:57.110 --> 00:48:58.760
we make in our theories.

00:48:58.760 --> 00:49:00.530
It matters for the
progress of science.

00:49:00.530 --> 00:49:04.190
And it matters beyond just
the realm of science as well.

00:49:04.190 --> 00:49:06.410
It matters for the entire world.

00:49:06.410 --> 00:49:08.540
Remember, throughout
the history of humanity,

00:49:08.540 --> 00:49:13.610
this was at least in
Europe, the dominant way

00:49:13.610 --> 00:49:15.860
of thinking about what
the universe looked

00:49:15.860 --> 00:49:17.860
like throughout most
of human history.

00:49:17.860 --> 00:49:21.620
The Earth is at the center,
and everything moves around us.

00:49:21.620 --> 00:49:26.600
And it wasn't until
Copernicus in the 1500s,

00:49:26.600 --> 00:49:29.360
that people started seriously
considering the possibility

00:49:29.360 --> 00:49:32.880
that the Earth is not at
the center of everything.

00:49:32.880 --> 00:49:35.420
And without that move,
without Copernicus uncentering

00:49:35.420 --> 00:49:37.520
the Earth, it seems
unlikely that Darwin

00:49:37.520 --> 00:49:39.840
would have had the
audacity to say, yeah,

00:49:39.840 --> 00:49:41.840
humans are not at the
center of creation either.

00:49:41.840 --> 00:49:45.680
We are just another part
of a giant tree of life.

00:49:45.680 --> 00:49:48.770
And without those two insights,
our entire modern world,

00:49:48.770 --> 00:49:52.460
not just science, but
culture, art, movies,

00:49:52.460 --> 00:49:55.070
would look entirely different.

00:49:55.070 --> 00:49:58.100
