There are proposed modifications
to quantum mechanics

00:59:37.964 --> 00:59:40.130
that would also solve the
measurement problem called

00:59:40.130 --> 00:59:42.110
spontaneous collapse theories.

00:59:42.110 --> 00:59:45.260
Those are fundamentally
non-deterministic.

00:59:45.260 --> 00:59:48.537
So it depends on what you pick.

00:59:48.537 --> 00:59:50.870
As for what it means for
things to not be deterministic,

00:59:50.870 --> 00:59:53.150
it means that sometimes
the future of the world

00:59:53.150 --> 00:59:57.520
is not fully specified by
the past state of the world.

00:59:57.520 --> 01:00:00.250
AUDIENCE: An effort to figure
out the nature of the universe

01:00:00.250 --> 01:00:03.460
and how the universe works,
until or unless it can come up

01:00:03.460 --> 01:00:08.710
with some kind of device
that can measure or detect

01:00:08.710 --> 01:00:12.729
that which energy
and mass actually is.

01:00:12.729 --> 01:00:14.770
Because when you tear
apart both mass and energy,

01:00:14.770 --> 01:00:16.510
eventually you're
left with nothing,

01:00:16.510 --> 01:00:20.320
but obviously, mass energy
must be coming from something.

01:00:20.320 --> 01:00:24.880
Do you think we'll ever come
up with some means made up

01:00:24.880 --> 01:00:28.360
of mass or energy that
can detect that which

01:00:28.360 --> 01:00:30.040
underlies mass and energy?

01:00:30.040 --> 01:00:33.550
Do you think that's
ever possible?

01:00:33.550 --> 01:00:36.922
ADAM BECKER: I think that mass
is just one form of energy.

01:00:36.922 --> 01:00:38.380
I wouldn't say that
mass and energy

01:00:38.380 --> 01:00:39.620
are two sides of the same coin.

01:00:39.620 --> 01:00:41.453
I would say mass is
just one kind of energy,

01:00:41.453 --> 01:00:42.934
and what's
fundamental is energy.

01:00:42.934 --> 01:00:45.100
And that is the standard
view among most physicists,

01:00:45.100 --> 01:00:46.799
and I think it's probably right.

01:00:46.799 --> 01:00:49.090
Mass is a kind of energy the
same way kinetic energy is

01:00:49.090 --> 01:00:51.423
a kind of energy, the same
way heat is a kind of-- well,

01:00:51.423 --> 01:00:53.650
heat is a kind of
kinetic energy--

01:00:53.650 --> 01:00:56.380
the same with that potential
energy is a kind of energy.

01:00:56.380 --> 01:01:00.220
I think that what e equals
mc squared really says

01:01:00.220 --> 01:01:03.400
is that mass is
a form of energy.

01:01:03.400 --> 01:01:07.680
So yeah, I don't see a problem
there the way that you do.

01:01:07.680 --> 01:01:08.388
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

01:01:08.388 --> 01:01:09.326
Thank you.

01:01:12.610 --> 01:01:14.530
ALEX: Let's go back to the Dory.

01:01:14.530 --> 01:01:17.590
What is consciousness
according to quantum physics?

01:01:17.590 --> 01:01:19.738
ADAM BECKER: I don't
see a relationship.

01:01:19.738 --> 01:01:21.960
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:21.960 --> 01:01:24.870
OK let me be less flip.

01:01:24.870 --> 01:01:28.410
So I think that a
lot of people like

01:01:28.410 --> 01:01:30.510
to say that consciousness
has some relationship

01:01:30.510 --> 01:01:33.780
to quantum physics because
we don't fully understand

01:01:33.780 --> 01:01:36.390
what consciousness is and
because there's controversy

01:01:36.390 --> 01:01:38.380
over the solution of
the measurement problem.

01:01:38.380 --> 01:01:39.630
So if we put together
the two things

01:01:39.630 --> 01:01:41.171
that we don't
understand, maybe we'll

01:01:41.171 --> 01:01:44.040
get just one thing
we don't understand.

01:01:44.040 --> 01:01:47.307
And some serious physicists
have, at various points,

01:01:47.307 --> 01:01:49.890
proposed that consciousness is
the solution to the measurement

01:01:49.890 --> 01:01:52.800
problem, that it's consciousness
that collapses wave functions.

01:01:52.800 --> 01:01:54.930
Eugene Wigner believed
this at one point

01:01:54.930 --> 01:01:56.940
until he was set straight.

01:01:56.940 --> 01:01:58.920
I don't think that
that's correct.

01:01:58.920 --> 01:02:00.570
I think that if
that is correct, we

01:02:00.570 --> 01:02:03.540
need to do a lot more work
to prove that it's correct

01:02:03.540 --> 01:02:06.780
because there are definitely
viable alternatives to that

01:02:06.780 --> 01:02:08.850
on the table.

01:02:08.850 --> 01:02:11.370
I think that if consciousness
causes collapse,

01:02:11.370 --> 01:02:14.550
we have questions like,
OK, what is consciousness.

01:02:14.550 --> 01:02:16.740
By what virtues does
it cause collapse?

01:02:16.740 --> 01:02:18.420
What property does
it have that allows

01:02:18.420 --> 01:02:19.800
it to collapse wave functions?

01:02:19.800 --> 01:02:21.850
What else can collapse
wave functions?

01:02:21.850 --> 01:02:23.915
It's a whole host
of other problems.

01:02:23.915 --> 01:02:25.290
And I don't think
quantum physics

01:02:25.290 --> 01:02:27.780
itself says anything about
the nature of consciousness.

01:02:27.780 --> 01:02:30.150
I think that that's--

01:02:30.150 --> 01:02:35.950
what consciousness is, is a good
question for a different field.

01:02:35.950 --> 01:02:39.590
AUDIENCE: So I remember reading
30 years ago these books,

01:02:39.590 --> 01:02:41.810
following up to that, the
"Dancing Wu Li Masters"

01:02:41.810 --> 01:02:43.157
and "The Tao of Consciousness".

01:02:43.157 --> 01:02:44.990
And I think the whole
premise of those books

01:02:44.990 --> 01:02:50.622
was what can cause a
collapse in these functions.

01:02:50.622 --> 01:02:51.830
Is that basically the whole--

01:02:51.830 --> 01:02:54.496
that was the whole misconception
of those books, that they based

01:02:54.496 --> 01:02:56.750
their entire framework around?

01:02:56.750 --> 01:02:58.540
ADAM BECKER: Yes, so
the question was--

01:02:58.540 --> 01:03:00.040
AUDIENCE: And can
I ask a follow up,

01:03:00.040 --> 01:03:04.559
which is what can cause a
collapse in this function.

01:03:04.559 --> 01:03:06.850
ADAM BECKER: Sure, so first
I realized I never actually

01:03:06.850 --> 01:03:08.141
repeated the original question.

01:03:08.141 --> 01:03:08.890
I just answered.

01:03:08.890 --> 01:03:11.473
Which was, what is consciousness
according to quantum physics.

01:03:11.473 --> 01:03:12.730
That's the answer I just gave.

01:03:12.730 --> 01:03:15.340
Your question was these books,
"The Dancing Wu Li Masters",

01:03:15.340 --> 01:03:18.410
"The Tao of Physics", was
this about a misunderstanding

01:03:18.410 --> 01:03:20.410
of what causes the collapse
of the wave function

01:03:20.410 --> 01:03:23.050
and then what does cause the
collapse of the wave function.

01:03:23.050 --> 01:03:26.800
I think that those books were--

01:03:26.800 --> 01:03:29.675
full disclaimer, I
have not actually

01:03:29.675 --> 01:03:31.550
read both of those books
from cover to cover.

01:03:31.550 --> 01:03:33.640
I flipped through
them, but I think

01:03:33.640 --> 01:03:36.520
that part of the
deal with those books

01:03:36.520 --> 01:03:39.970
is that they are
interested in going

01:03:39.970 --> 01:03:42.850
after these questions that were
seen as verboten for physicists

01:03:42.850 --> 01:03:45.130
by the Copenhagen
Interpretation, which

01:03:45.130 --> 01:03:46.930
the shut up part of
shut up and calculate

01:03:46.930 --> 01:03:49.330
has a sort of
moralistic sense to it.

01:03:49.330 --> 01:03:53.380
Like not only don't you
need to ask these questions,

01:03:53.380 --> 01:03:55.300
you shouldn't ask
these questions.

01:03:55.300 --> 01:03:58.060
Good physicists don't
ask these questions.

01:03:58.060 --> 01:04:01.390
There's something wrong with
you if you ask these questions.

01:04:01.390 --> 01:04:03.280
Which is bullshit.

01:04:03.280 --> 01:04:04.840
But I think that
these books were

01:04:04.840 --> 01:04:07.379
motivated in part by a desire
to ask those questions.

01:04:07.379 --> 01:04:08.920
And then they said,
OK, and let's ask

01:04:08.920 --> 01:04:10.900
other questions that are
verboten to physicists

01:04:10.900 --> 01:04:13.000
like is there ESP.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:14.770
What about telekinesis?

01:04:14.770 --> 01:04:17.560
What about the relationship
between religion and quantum

01:04:17.560 --> 01:04:19.940
physics, consciousness
and quantum physics?

01:04:19.940 --> 01:04:24.010
And I think throwing in all that
stuff really confuses things,

01:04:24.010 --> 01:04:25.720
but I think that they
were right to ask

01:04:25.720 --> 01:04:29.759
the question of what's going
on in wave function collapse.

01:04:29.759 --> 01:04:31.300
I also think that
they were motivated

01:04:31.300 --> 01:04:34.270
by this sort of desire
to see similarities

01:04:34.270 --> 01:04:39.880
between certain religions
and quantum physics.

01:04:39.880 --> 01:04:43.150
And just to talk about
that for a second

01:04:43.150 --> 01:04:46.200
before I get to your last
part of the question,

01:04:46.200 --> 01:04:47.590
I think it's
generally a bad idea

01:04:47.590 --> 01:04:50.770
to try to find parallels
between religion and science

01:04:50.770 --> 01:04:55.420
because science has this
nasty habit of being refined

01:04:55.420 --> 01:04:58.870
and corrected and proved wrong
or scientific theories get

01:04:58.870 --> 01:04:59.470
overturned.

01:04:59.470 --> 01:05:03.130
So if you try to latch
your religious philosophy

01:05:03.130 --> 01:05:04.750
onto a particular
scientific truth,

01:05:04.750 --> 01:05:06.490
there's a good chance that
your religious philosophy

01:05:06.490 --> 01:05:08.200
is going to go down
the toilet when

01:05:08.200 --> 01:05:12.490
that truth is found to be not
quite true or completely wrong.

01:05:12.490 --> 01:05:14.475
So I'm not very sympathetic
to that project,

01:05:14.475 --> 01:05:15.850
and I don't think
that people who

01:05:15.850 --> 01:05:19.090
like religion should be either.

01:05:19.090 --> 01:05:24.240
Anyway as for what actually
causes the collapse of the wave

01:05:24.240 --> 01:05:25.999
function, I don't know.

01:05:25.999 --> 01:05:27.790
I don't even know if
functions do collapse.

01:05:27.790 --> 01:05:30.550
If they don't collapse,
we live in many worlds.

01:05:30.550 --> 01:05:35.680
Or we have something like pilot
wave theory where it collapse,

01:05:35.680 --> 01:05:38.980
it's something that's
relative to other stuff.

01:05:38.980 --> 01:05:40.680
It's more complicated than that.

01:05:40.680 --> 01:05:42.912
Or we have something like
a spontaneous collapse

01:05:42.912 --> 01:05:44.620
theory where collapse
is a real objective

01:05:44.620 --> 01:05:46.960
thing that happens at random.

01:05:46.960 --> 01:05:48.590
Or one of the other options.

01:05:48.590 --> 01:05:50.290
So I don't know what causes it.

01:05:50.290 --> 01:05:53.080
But either wave function
collapse is happening

01:05:53.080 --> 01:05:55.960
or something is causing it to
look like function collapse is

01:05:55.960 --> 01:05:56.770
happening.

01:05:56.770 --> 01:05:59.050
And figuring out
what's going on there

01:05:59.050 --> 01:06:02.650
is a legitimate area of
scientific inquiry called

01:06:02.650 --> 01:06:05.170
foundations of
quantum physics that

01:06:05.170 --> 01:06:08.260
still has a bad reputation among
physicists even to this day,

01:06:08.260 --> 01:06:12.050
though it's less bad
than it used to be.

01:06:12.050 --> 01:06:14.770
ALEX: I've heard you mention
many times that there's

01:06:14.770 --> 01:06:20.110
sort of this big split between
physicists and philosophers

01:06:20.110 --> 01:06:23.950
of physics because
physicists don't know

01:06:23.950 --> 01:06:27.310
any philosophy while
philosophers of physics

01:06:27.310 --> 01:06:29.350
know a lot of physics.

01:06:29.350 --> 01:06:31.310
I'm also thinking of--

01:06:31.310 --> 01:06:33.440
I'm probably going to
misquote it, a quote by--

01:06:33.440 --> 01:06:36.250
I think it might be
some modern philosopher.

01:06:36.250 --> 01:06:37.720
It might be Dan Dennett--

01:06:37.720 --> 01:06:40.210
I don't know-- who
said something like,

01:06:40.210 --> 01:06:41.980
there's no science
without philosophy.

01:06:41.980 --> 01:06:45.190
There's only science with
unexamined philosophy

01:06:45.190 --> 01:06:46.620
or something like that, which--

01:06:46.620 --> 01:06:47.410
ADAM BECKER: Yeah that sounds
like something Dennett would

01:06:47.410 --> 01:06:47.910
say.

01:06:47.910 --> 01:06:49.780
ALEX: Yeah, and
so I thought maybe

01:06:49.780 --> 01:06:53.260
you might want to
comment on why is

01:06:53.260 --> 01:06:56.931
it that physicists don't
know any philosophy any more

01:06:56.931 --> 01:06:57.430
at least?

01:06:57.430 --> 01:06:59.180
ADAM BECKER: This is
a very good question.

01:06:59.180 --> 01:07:01.720
So the question is about
why physicists mostly

01:07:01.720 --> 01:07:03.790
don't seem to know
philosophy, but philosophers

01:07:03.790 --> 01:07:06.820
of physics, the serious ones,
tend to be very well schooled

01:07:06.820 --> 01:07:07.320
in physics.

01:07:07.320 --> 01:07:09.220
Many of them have
undergraduate or even

01:07:09.220 --> 01:07:15.139
PhDs in physics as
well as philosophy.

01:07:15.139 --> 01:07:16.930
Yeah, there's definitely
an asymmetry there

01:07:16.930 --> 01:07:18.471
where the philosophers
know much more

01:07:18.471 --> 01:07:21.490
physics than the
physicists know philosophy.

01:07:21.490 --> 01:07:24.880
As a physicist, I'm
interested in asymmetries.

01:07:24.880 --> 01:07:27.520
So yeah.

01:07:27.520 --> 01:07:36.610
I think that basically,
this is due to a variety

01:07:36.610 --> 01:07:40.420
of historical and
cultural factors.

01:07:40.420 --> 01:07:45.090
I think that that quote, whether
it's Dan Dennett or whoever who

01:07:45.090 --> 01:07:47.790
said that, it's definitely
true that physicists

01:07:47.790 --> 01:07:51.746
engage in philosophy all the
time while doing physics.

01:07:51.746 --> 01:07:52.620
It's just part of it.

01:07:55.220 --> 01:07:58.084
And then the question is, OK
why don't they admit that.

01:07:58.084 --> 01:07:59.250
Why don't they look at this?

01:07:59.250 --> 01:08:01.652
Well, philosophy has a
bit of a bad reputation

01:08:01.652 --> 01:08:02.360
among physicists.

01:08:02.360 --> 01:08:05.160
So why does it have
a bad reputation?

01:08:05.160 --> 01:08:06.850
That's a hard
question to answer.

01:08:06.850 --> 01:08:10.050
I think part of it has to do
with those same factors at work

01:08:10.050 --> 01:08:13.140
after World War II where
academia just got flooded

01:08:13.140 --> 01:08:17.430
with more people and this led
to a sort of Balkanization

01:08:17.430 --> 01:08:20.880
of academia and the walls
went up between departments.

01:08:20.880 --> 01:08:23.002
It used to be that
physicists generally had

01:08:23.002 --> 01:08:24.210
some schooling in philosophy.

01:08:24.210 --> 01:08:26.319
Now, that's not necessary.

01:08:26.319 --> 01:08:29.200
I'm not saying that we should
go back to the good old days.

01:08:29.200 --> 01:08:30.580
There are plenty of problems.

01:08:30.580 --> 01:08:32.040
But I do think
that a liberal arts

01:08:32.040 --> 01:08:37.529
education is quite valuable
for doing almost anything.

01:08:37.529 --> 01:08:43.689
But I think that due to
that set of boundaries

01:08:43.689 --> 01:08:45.490
between academic
disciplines, that

01:08:45.490 --> 01:08:48.490
has made it easy for physicists
to be ignorant of philosophy.

01:08:48.490 --> 01:08:50.170
And then it's easy
for misconceptions

01:08:50.170 --> 01:08:52.180
about philosophy, like
it doesn't make progress,

01:08:52.180 --> 01:08:53.721
they just ask the
same questions over

01:08:53.721 --> 01:08:56.513
and over again, they're
not like us physicists,

01:08:56.513 --> 01:08:59.124
that kind of thing to show up.

01:08:59.124 --> 01:09:00.790
Philosophers also
have a habit of asking

01:09:00.790 --> 01:09:01.899
very annoying questions.

01:09:01.899 --> 01:09:03.315
This is a long and
proud tradition

01:09:03.315 --> 01:09:05.300
going back to Socrates.

01:09:05.300 --> 01:09:09.250
Now most of us don't have to
drink hemlock as a result.

01:09:09.250 --> 01:09:12.430
But one way of dismissing
annoying questions

01:09:12.430 --> 01:09:15.130
is to say that the people who
ask the annoying questions

01:09:15.130 --> 01:09:18.240
are stupid and don't
need to be listened to.

01:09:18.240 --> 01:09:22.520
Or you make them drink hemlock.

01:09:22.520 --> 01:09:24.790
So that's another thing.

01:09:24.790 --> 01:09:28.490
I think that there are
some philosophers who are,

01:09:28.490 --> 01:09:32.979
let's say, skeptical
of scientific progress.

01:09:32.979 --> 01:09:37.300
This has to do with a
split within philosophy

01:09:37.300 --> 01:09:39.680
between analytic and
continental philosophy,

01:09:39.680 --> 01:09:42.279
which is a whole other thing.

01:09:42.279 --> 01:09:45.939
And those names are
incidentally not relevant at all

01:09:45.939 --> 01:09:47.130
to what those fields study.

01:09:47.130 --> 01:09:49.390
They're just
historical artifacts.

01:09:49.390 --> 01:09:55.000
But continental philosophy
tends to be a little bit more

01:09:55.000 --> 01:09:58.570
skeptical of authority in
any form and in many ways,

01:09:58.570 --> 01:10:00.160
rightly so.

01:10:00.160 --> 01:10:03.070
And it tends to ask questions
about scientific authority,

01:10:03.070 --> 01:10:05.610
which if you interpret
them naively or if you're

01:10:05.610 --> 01:10:09.190
a bad continental philosopher,
can lead to people saying

01:10:09.190 --> 01:10:11.660
things like, oh science is
just as good as any other way

01:10:11.660 --> 01:10:12.920
of trying to solve problems.

01:10:12.920 --> 01:10:14.620
And that's some bullshit.

01:10:14.620 --> 01:10:16.982
And scientists would be
rightly dismissive of that,

01:10:16.982 --> 01:10:18.940
and then they might lump
all other philosophers

01:10:18.940 --> 01:10:19.481
in with that.

01:10:19.481 --> 01:10:21.880
But that's just a
guess on my part.

01:10:21.880 --> 01:10:24.040
So I think that,
basically, philosophy

01:10:24.040 --> 01:10:29.200
has a very bad reputation
for a variety of reasons.

01:10:29.200 --> 01:10:31.380
It used to not.

01:10:31.380 --> 01:10:34.360
Bohr did read too
much Kant, but it's

01:10:34.360 --> 01:10:37.330
better than reading nothing.

01:10:37.330 --> 01:10:40.900
Einstein read a lot
of Mach and Leibniz

01:10:40.900 --> 01:10:46.570
and Spinoza and other
great philosophers, Hume

01:10:46.570 --> 01:10:49.190
in particular.

01:10:49.190 --> 01:10:52.282
Yeah, I think that
it's a real shame

01:10:52.282 --> 01:10:53.490
that that asymmetry is there.

01:10:53.490 --> 01:10:55.090
I think that
philosophers of physics

01:10:55.090 --> 01:10:58.330
have a lot to teach physicists
and have a lot of value

01:10:58.330 --> 01:11:00.020
to offer.

01:11:00.020 --> 01:11:04.870
And I think it's really awful
when prominent scientists say

01:11:04.870 --> 01:11:07.420
stupid things about
philosophy, which happens

01:11:07.420 --> 01:11:08.842
more often than it should.

01:11:08.842 --> 01:11:10.300
ALEX: So the next
question is, what

01:11:10.300 --> 01:11:14.896
about the success of quantum
electrodynamics in predicting?

01:11:14.896 --> 01:11:16.270
I mean, it seems
like your answer

01:11:16.270 --> 01:11:19.690
is the past hour-long
talk, roughly.

01:11:19.690 --> 01:11:20.700
ADAM BECKER: Yeah.

01:11:20.700 --> 01:11:23.410
So the success of quantum
electrodynamics, yeah,

01:11:23.410 --> 01:11:23.967
absolutely.

01:11:23.967 --> 01:11:26.050
Quantum electrodynamics
and quantum field theories

01:11:26.050 --> 01:11:27.670
in general are
extremely successful.

01:11:27.670 --> 01:11:30.490
I'm not debating the
success of quantum physics.

01:11:30.490 --> 01:11:32.082
It absolutely works.

01:11:32.082 --> 01:11:33.790
It's just an incomplete
picture of what's

01:11:33.790 --> 01:11:35.140
going on in the world.

01:11:35.140 --> 01:11:37.180
And throwing in quantum
field theory, as opposed

01:11:37.180 --> 01:11:39.031
to just vanilla
quantum mechanics,

01:11:39.031 --> 01:11:40.030
doesn't fix the problem.

01:11:40.030 --> 01:11:42.040
If anything, it makes it worse.

01:11:42.040 --> 01:11:44.500
Some people will say, oh,
quantum field theory definitely

01:11:44.500 --> 01:11:46.780
gets you around Bell's
theorem because quantum field

01:11:46.780 --> 01:11:48.820
theory is designed
to be compatible

01:11:48.820 --> 01:11:50.399
with special relativity.

01:11:50.399 --> 01:11:52.690
There are these things called
the commutation relations

01:11:52.690 --> 01:11:57.160
that ensure this relationship.

01:11:57.160 --> 01:11:59.320
No, that doesn't solve
the problem at all

01:11:59.320 --> 01:12:01.870
because you still have the
problem of wave function

01:12:01.870 --> 01:12:03.490
collapse in quantum
field theory.

01:12:03.490 --> 01:12:05.530
And that is subject
to Bell's theorem,

01:12:05.530 --> 01:12:08.620
and that does not get solved
by the commutation relations.

01:12:08.620 --> 01:12:11.110
And this is a massive
misunderstanding that still

01:12:11.110 --> 01:12:12.760
persists among physicists.

01:12:12.760 --> 01:12:14.500
And that's just a
mathematical mistake.

01:12:14.500 --> 01:12:15.940
That's just an error.

01:12:15.940 --> 01:12:18.520
Quantum field theory
doesn't solve this problem.

01:12:18.520 --> 01:12:20.650
Quantum field theory
also has other problems.

01:12:20.650 --> 01:12:22.480
It works incredibly
well, but it also

01:12:22.480 --> 01:12:25.540
has its own unique issues
that mathematicians

01:12:25.540 --> 01:12:27.349
worry about like
re-normalization

01:12:27.349 --> 01:12:29.140
or something called
Hogg's theorem, which--

01:12:29.140 --> 01:12:31.225
don't get me started.

01:12:31.225 --> 01:12:32.020
ALEX: I won't.

01:12:32.020 --> 01:12:33.250
ADAM BECKER: Yeah, anyway.

01:12:33.250 --> 01:12:34.570
So yeah.

01:12:34.570 --> 01:12:36.080
Quantum field theory is great.

01:12:36.080 --> 01:12:36.910
I love it.

01:12:36.910 --> 01:12:38.290
It is a wonderful theory.

01:12:38.290 --> 01:12:39.820
Doesn't solve these problems.

01:12:39.820 --> 01:12:41.940
ALEX: OK, we have time
for one more question.

01:12:41.940 --> 01:12:44.755
So since you haven't had time.

01:12:44.755 --> 01:12:47.410
AUDIENCE: Just a follow-up
to your previous answer.

01:12:47.410 --> 01:12:49.420
Without speculating
about why physicists

01:12:49.420 --> 01:12:54.130
have a bad image of philosophy,
can you, from your research,

01:12:54.130 --> 01:12:57.540
pinpoint when this attitude--
when did physicists

01:12:57.540 --> 01:13:00.280
start to have a bad
image of philosophy?

01:13:00.280 --> 01:13:02.170
Since you're a physicist
and a philosopher,

01:13:02.170 --> 01:13:04.741
can you give us your
attitude towards philosophy?

01:13:04.741 --> 01:13:06.990
Noting that your answer
doesn't need to be monolithic,

01:13:06.990 --> 01:13:09.737
is there some part of philosophy
that you think is worthwhile?

01:13:09.737 --> 01:13:11.320
ADAM BECKER: I don't
know exactly when

01:13:11.320 --> 01:13:11.980
the split happened.

01:13:11.980 --> 01:13:14.320
I don't think it's something
that happened all at once.

01:13:14.320 --> 01:13:16.360
I think that World
War II has a lot

01:13:16.360 --> 01:13:20.230
to do with it, which is in
a way kind of boring answer.

01:13:20.230 --> 01:13:22.780
Like one of the central
events of the 20th century

01:13:22.780 --> 01:13:24.100
had a lot of effect.

01:13:24.100 --> 01:13:26.570
That's a somewhat boring answer.

01:13:26.570 --> 01:13:28.840
But yeah, I mean,
World War II really

01:13:28.840 --> 01:13:30.400
changed the way that
academia worked.

01:13:30.400 --> 01:13:35.410
It really moved the center of
physics from Germany to the US.

01:13:35.410 --> 01:13:38.440
The US already had a tradition
of much more pragmatic

01:13:38.440 --> 01:13:41.470
approaches to the
sciences, which--

01:13:41.470 --> 01:13:47.120
that's going to make
philosophy look less useful.

01:13:47.120 --> 01:13:48.730
There was also this
school of thought

01:13:48.730 --> 01:13:51.070
called logical
positivism, which was

01:13:51.070 --> 01:13:53.800
very influential in the first
half of the 20th century.

01:13:56.650 --> 01:13:58.540
And it was also a
school of thought

01:13:58.540 --> 01:14:01.690
which was dismissive of
certain kinds of philosophy.

01:14:01.690 --> 01:14:06.640
And then, around the time that
physics and philosophy kind of

01:14:06.640 --> 01:14:10.180
decoupled around the end of
World War II, that was also

01:14:10.180 --> 01:14:13.510
the beginning of the real
decline of logical positivism,

01:14:13.510 --> 01:14:16.630
even among philosophers who
were sympathetic to the aims

01:14:16.630 --> 01:14:17.980
of the positivists.

01:14:17.980 --> 01:14:22.750
And so by the time positivism
was fully discredited,

01:14:22.750 --> 01:14:25.060
physicists couldn't
really get the memo

01:14:25.060 --> 01:14:28.150
and still used a lot of
positivist-ish arguments,

01:14:28.150 --> 01:14:30.880
really knock-off positivist
arguments like, oh,

01:14:30.880 --> 01:14:33.900
it's meaningless to talk about
things that you can't see.

01:14:33.900 --> 01:14:37.000
They would use those arguments
to dismiss most of philosophy

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:40.940
when, in fact, philosophy
is decades old counter

01:14:40.940 --> 01:14:43.122
arguments explaining
why that doesn't work.

01:14:43.122 --> 01:14:44.830
And when you present
those to physicists,

01:14:44.830 --> 01:14:49.916
they will sort of stare at
you slack jawed like did you

01:14:49.916 --> 01:14:51.040
come up with that yourself.

01:14:51.040 --> 01:14:52.300
That seems very profound.

01:14:52.300 --> 01:14:54.466
No, that argument is older
than both of us combined.

01:14:58.781 --> 01:14:59.280
So yeah.

01:14:59.280 --> 01:15:04.150
As for my take on philosophy,
I think that in general, it

01:15:04.150 --> 01:15:08.380
is usually a bad idea to
dismiss almost any area

01:15:08.380 --> 01:15:10.550
of serious academic inquiry.

01:15:10.550 --> 01:15:15.730
There are exceptions, such
as evolutionary psychology.

01:15:19.860 --> 01:15:21.430
I like psychology.

01:15:21.430 --> 01:15:22.630
Evolutionary psychology?

01:15:26.170 --> 01:15:28.960
But I think that
most of philosophy

01:15:28.960 --> 01:15:30.400
has something worthwhile.

01:15:30.400 --> 01:15:34.540
I think philosophy of physics,
in the analytic tradition,

01:15:34.540 --> 01:15:36.460
has done a lot of
really great work

01:15:36.460 --> 01:15:38.980
in particular because it's
gone after these questions

01:15:38.980 --> 01:15:41.200
that physicists have
largely ignored.

01:15:41.200 --> 01:15:43.600
But I also think that
philosophy of science

01:15:43.600 --> 01:15:46.060
really helps to clear up a
lot of misunderstandings that

01:15:46.060 --> 01:15:49.390
are prevalent among scientists
of all stripes about how

01:15:49.390 --> 01:15:50.120
science works.

01:15:50.120 --> 01:15:53.470
There are some naive ideas
there that philosophers

01:15:53.470 --> 01:15:55.990
have help to kick to the curb.

01:16:01.460 --> 01:16:05.450
I think that if you think
that you have a simple answer

01:16:05.450 --> 01:16:09.320
to a deep question, talking to
a philosopher for a few minutes

01:16:09.320 --> 01:16:11.640
will usually tell you
that you're wrong.

01:16:11.640 --> 01:16:15.750
And I think that it's good
to experience being wrong.

01:16:15.750 --> 01:16:18.780
I think that's an important
part of the human experience,

01:16:18.780 --> 01:16:21.560
and I think that it's
good to think deeply

01:16:21.560 --> 01:16:24.170
about strange questions.

01:16:24.170 --> 01:16:26.870
And I think that the questions
philosophers tend to ask--

01:16:26.870 --> 01:16:30.040
and this might be another
source of the problem--

01:16:30.040 --> 01:16:31.790
philosophers will ask
questions that sound

01:16:31.790 --> 01:16:33.680
like they have obvious
answers to scientists.

01:16:33.680 --> 01:16:39.360
Like OK, what is a physical law?

01:16:39.360 --> 01:16:41.650
OK, that doesn't
seem interesting.

01:16:41.650 --> 01:16:42.940
That seems obvious.

01:16:42.940 --> 01:16:45.857
And then they go on about it for
five minutes, like oh, OK yeah.

01:16:45.857 --> 01:16:48.440
I see what they're asking, but
I think there's an easy answer.

01:16:48.440 --> 01:16:50.320
And then they go on about
it for 10 more minutes,

01:16:50.320 --> 01:16:52.403
and you realize you don't
even know where the hell

01:16:52.403 --> 01:16:53.710
you are anymore.

01:16:53.710 --> 01:16:56.331
And I mean, I think that
that's a really good experience

01:16:56.331 --> 01:16:56.830
to have.

01:16:56.830 --> 01:16:58.480
I think it's good to
understand weight.

01:16:58.480 --> 01:17:00.021
These things that
we take for granted

01:17:00.021 --> 01:17:02.020
might be way more
complicated than we think.

01:17:02.020 --> 01:17:04.900
And there is also a
long and proud tradition

01:17:04.900 --> 01:17:08.890
in science of doing science
and damn the torpedoes,

01:17:08.890 --> 01:17:12.750
forget the philosophical or
mathematical foundations.

01:17:12.750 --> 01:17:15.370
I'm not even saying that
shut up and calculate

01:17:15.370 --> 01:17:17.110
was always the wrong approach.

01:17:17.110 --> 01:17:19.480
It's certainly not the case
that every single physicist

01:17:19.480 --> 01:17:22.670
should be thinking about quantum
foundations all the time.

01:17:22.670 --> 01:17:24.550
It's just that
moralistic thing of no,

01:17:24.550 --> 01:17:26.500
you should shut
up and calculate,

01:17:26.500 --> 01:17:29.340
a good physicist shuts
up and calculates.

01:17:29.340 --> 01:17:31.450
That's some bullshit.

01:17:31.450 --> 01:17:34.090
These questions are
legitimate parts of science,

01:17:34.090 --> 01:17:37.540
and the boundary between
science and philosophy

01:17:37.540 --> 01:17:41.140
is and always has been
permeable, just as it

01:17:41.140 --> 01:17:43.529
is between any two disciplines.

01:17:43.529 --> 01:17:45.070
ALEX: And yeah, it's
been a pleasure.

01:17:45.070 --> 01:17:46.612
And thank you all
of you for coming.

01:17:46.612 --> 01:17:47.820
ADAM BECKER: Yeah, thank you.

01:17:47.820 --> 01:17:50.270
[APPLAUSE]

